

"""
beta_desynchronization_movement.py
------------------------------------
Beta oscillations (13-30 Hz) over motor cortex are the brain's
"status quo" signal. When nothing is changing and no movement
is planned, beta is high — it maintains the current motor state.
 
The moment you plan or initiate a movement, beta drops sharply.
This is event-related desynchronization (ERD), and it happens
200-500ms BEFORE the movement itself — meaning beta suppression
is preparatory, not reactive.
 
After the movement ends, beta rebounds above baseline (ERS —
event-related synchronization). This rebound is called the
post-movement beta rebound (PMBR) and is thought to actively
suppress further movement and "reset" the motor system.
 
The beta-movement relationship is one of the most studied
phenomena in motor neuroscience and has direct clinical relevance
in Parkinson's disease, where pathologically elevated beta in
basal ganglia correlates with motor freezing and rigidity.
 
References:
  - Pfurtscheller et al. (1996) Electroencephalogr Clin Neurophysiol
  - Kilavik et al. (2013) Neuroscience 250:287
  - Little & Brown (2014) Exp Neurol 245:34  — Parkinson's beta
  - Engel & Fries (2010) Curr Opin Neurobiol 20:156
  - Jenkinson & Brown (2011) Trends Neurosci 34:611
 
pip install matplotlib numpy scipy
"""
 
